<p class="has-side-note">
  “This is outrageous!” said Merlot Bot. “You’re shining us on! You moonsayin' son of a bitch! You expressed every confidence that you could kill the boar when Daniel was here! And now you’re fawning all over this immortal boar! Why say he can be killed when he can’t?”
  <p class="side-note" style="border-left: 5px solid #6495ed">"You moonsayin' son of a bitch!"--Merlot Bot</p>
</p>
<p>
“If it can be killed, we’re the team that can do it. But we need Kraken’s wherewithal. And with this thing out there, gobbling up everything, uprooting everything, there’s nothing else we’d rather hunt, even if we fail. Plus, we need to eat.”
</p>
<p>
“And what does he eat?” asked Merlot Bot. “I mean, I know he’s torn open silos with his tusks, and wallowed over entire wheat fields, and threatened this entire island with famine. But is there anything that can entice him. Anything special catch his eye?”
</p>
<p>
“He’s a fool for acorns,” confided Stalwart.
</p>
<p>
Down in the lobby, Daniel Kraken was fastidiously pinching cinnamon ticks from Big Data’s dewlap, squishing them between the crepe skinned tips of his fingers before loudly slurping the squished disks of ticks into his mouth. There were no natural sources of cinnamon on the island, and Daniel, besotted with these dogs and homesick for the spice, was almost shivering with pleasure, and had to bring the full force of his industrialist’s discipline to bear to keep from nibbling the ticks directly from the dog’s neck. Sometimes a particularly thick tick would escape a thorough chewing, and the spiced, still struggling arachnid would hit Daniel’s throat at an odd angle, causing the old man to hack and wheeze.
</p>
<p>
“Wow gross,” remarked Mitsubishi Gallant.
</p>
<p>
“I know, right?” barked Carbon Neutral.
</p>
<p>
Back upstairs, Merlot Bot was proposing a way to coax the Butterfly Boar to its doom.
</p>
<p>
“A great chain of motion activated acorn feeders!” he shouted, waving his brass hands over the map of the island that occupied an entire wall of Daniel’s study. “You’ll only have to stock and set them once. Whenever something as large as the Butterfly Boar draws near (and nothing else is as large as this monster) the feeders will activate, spray out an initial circle of acorns to get its attention, then turn towards the next feeder in the chain and fire its last batch at it, so that the animal is compelled to move on to the next feeder. So on and so forth until it reaches a battleground of our choosing.”
</p>
<p>
“What you’re talking about is a fairy tale, a child plunking his marble collection on the kitchen table to try and help with the family finances,” said Stalwart. “There’s no technology that we possess that can manufacture and deploy such devices.
</p>
<p>
“Leave that to me,” said Merlot Bot.
